"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428477","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-11-20","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave on 16 November 2015 to Question 15511 to the hon. Member for Strangford (Mr Shannon).</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2015-11-20T14:22:51.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428477/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428477/answer","20151116_15511_Veterans_Cancer[1].docx","20151116 - QnA extract on Veterans Cancer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428477/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-11-16","Veterans: Mesothelioma","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will review compensation payments to armed forces veterans who served prior to 1987 and have contracted mesothelioma as a result of being exposed to asbestos while under military orders.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","16351"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428478","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-11-30","<p>The UK is clear that the best way to achieve a two-state solution is through negotiations between the Israeli Government and the Palestinian Authority. However, there must be an environment conducive to peace, and we are therefore urging all parties to de-escalate current tensions.</p><p>On 9 October, the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond) spoke to President Abbas and urged him to do everything in his power to reduce tensions and restore calm. Officials at our Embassy in Tel Aviv discuss the situation frequently with Israeli officials. Most recently, on 19 November, our Ambassador to Tel Aviv discussed the ongoing violence with Gilad Erdan, the Israeli Minister for Strategic Affairs, Public Security and Information.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-11-30T14:00:45.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428478/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428478/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428478/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-11-16","Israel: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent steps the Government has taken to advance peace talks in Israel and the Palestinian territories.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","16491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428479","Department of Health","false","2015-11-24","<p>Minor ailment schemes are commissioned locally by NHS England and clinical commissioning groups in many parts of England to meet local need. As part of its urgent and emergency care strategy, NHS England has run campaigns for the last two winters to encourage wider use of community pharmacies to treat coughs and colds. This year’s campaign Stay Well This Winter, launched on 2 November, directs people to their local pharmacy to seek advice on common ailments and advises people who feel unwell to get help from their pharmacy team quickly before it gets more serious.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-11-24T12:05:53.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428479/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428479/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428479/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-11-16","Pharmacy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will promote the development of a pharmacist-led common ailments service to reduce winter pressures on A&E departments and GP practices.","false","Biography information for Alex Chalk","Cheltenham","Alex Chalk","16349"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428480","Home Office","false","2015-11-24","<p>Data on entry clearance visas is produced quarterly. The information is provided for Q4 2013 onwards in the attachedtable.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-11-24T15:53:38.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428480/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428480/answer","Copy of table 16338.xlsx","Entry clearance visit visas","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428480/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-16","Visas: Palestinians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the number of Palestinians is who have applied for visit visas for the UK in each month since November 2013; and how many such applications were successful for each of those months.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart McDonald","16338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428481","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-11-23","<p>Sustainable fuels already form an important part of our energy mix and are contributing to the decarbonisation of the UK economy.</p><br /><p>During 2014 just under a fifth of renewable electricity generation came from bioenergy; bioenergy also forms about 94% of our total renewable heat generation; and in transport the Renewable Transport Fuel Obligation (RTFO) ensures that just under 5% of transport fuel comes from sustainable biofuels.</p><br /><p>The 2011 Carbon Plan set out a range of scenarios for how the UK could reduce emissions. This considered the role of renewable technologies under the different scenarios. The Government is due to set out next year the level of the fifth carbon budget, covering the years 2028-2032, and following this, a new emissions reduction plan will be published.</p><br /> <br />","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-11-23T15:17:43.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428481/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428481/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428481/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-11-16","Fuels: Sustainable Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether her Department has considered the potential contribution that sustainable fuels can make to supporting the decarbonisation of the UK economy.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart McDonald","16319"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428482","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-18","<p>This is a matter for the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), which is operationally independent from Government.</p><br /><p>These questions have been passed on to the FCA. They will reply directly to the Honorable Member Kirsten Oswald by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","16382","2015-11-18T14:03:13.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428482/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428482/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428482/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-16","Connaught Asset Management","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent progress there has been in holding to account directors responsible for promoting, managing and supervising Connaught Asset Management.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","16380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428483","HM Treasury","false","2015-11-18","<p>This is a matter for the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), which is operationally independent from Government.</p><br /><p>These questions have been passed on to the FCA. They will reply directly to the Honorable Member Kirsten Oswald by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","16380","2015-11-18T14:03:13.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428483/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428483/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428483/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-11-16","Connaught Asset Management","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of steps taken to hold to account companies and directors responsible for promoting and managing the affairs of Connaught Asset Management.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","16382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428484","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-11-23","<p>Where companies enter formal insolvency, there are powers under the Company Director’s Disqualification Act for the Secretary of State to apply to the court for the disqualification of directors who are found to be responsible for misconduct. Disqualification is a civil restriction which bars an individual from being appointed as a director, or being involved in the promotion, formation or management of a company for a period of between 2 and 15 years. Contravention of a disqualification is a criminal offence which may lead to prosecution and civil penalty.</p><p>That Act provides other grounds for disqualification of up to 15 years following misconduct in relation to companies not necessarily subject to insolvency proceedings, including disqualification on conviction of an indictable offence, for repeated breaches of company legislation and following investigations under the Companies Act.</p><p>In addition to disqualification, there are a number of criminal offences in the Insolvency Act for misconduct related to Insolvency, and other offences particularly in the Companies Act and Fraud Act.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-11-23T16:16:48.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428484/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428484/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428484/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-11-16","Directors: Misconduct","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what legislative provision exists to ensure that directors responsible for misconduct can be appropriately dealt with.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","16381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428485","Home Office","false","2015-12-02","<p>International students whose principal purpose for coming to the UK is to study English can use the Tier 4 (General) route of the points-based system or the short-term student route.</p><p>Applicants who wish to study a course below degree level under Tier 4 (General) must demonstrate that they are competent in English language at a minimum of level B1 in all four components (speaking, listening, reading and writing) on the Common European Framework of Reference for Languages. Those who wish to study a course at degree level or above must demonstrate they are competent at a minimum of level B2 in all four components.</p><p>Applicants who wish to study under the short-term student route are not required to demonstrate a prior knowledge of English language. English language courses may be studied for up to 11 months under this route.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-12-02T14:48:59.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428485/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428485/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428485/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-16","Overseas Students: Visas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what regulations on prior knowledge of English apply to applicants for Tier 4 visas where the student's principal purpose in entering the UK is to study English as a foreign language.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","16379"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428486","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-11-19","<p>Almshouses are exempt from the Right to Buy for council housing. This long-standing exemption will also apply to the extended Right to Buy for housing associations.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","16363","2015-11-19T13:27:17.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428486/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428486/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428486/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-11-16","Almshouses: Right to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what plans he has to revise the agreement reached with the National Housing Federation on right to buy to remove references to almshouses in the table of discretionary sales.","false","Biography information for Will Quince","Colchester","Will Quince","16364"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428487","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-11-19","<p>Almshouses are exempt from the Right to Buy for council housing. This long-standing exemption will also apply to the extended Right to Buy for housing associations.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","16364","2015-11-19T13:27:17.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428487/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428487/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428487/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-11-16","Almshouses: Right to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what plans he has to revise the agreement reached with the National Housing Federation on right to buy to expressly state that almshouse licensees will not have the right to buy.","false","Biography information for Will Quince","Colchester","Will Quince","16363"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428488","Department for Transport","false","2015-11-24","<p>The most recent assessment of the M61 was undertaken by the Highways Agency between 2012 and 2015 as part of the South Pennines Route Strategy. This utilised the advice and expertise of local councils and stakeholders. The final report was published in 2015 and is available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/416749/South_Pennines.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/416749/South_Pennines.pdf</a>.</p><br /><p>It identified traffic flow and congestion issues on the M61 where it merges with the M6 to the north and also where it approaches the M60 to the south. However no particular traffic flow and congestion problems were identified between Junctions 6 and 8.</p><br /><p>Highways England will revisit the evidence for the M61 as part of preparing the next iteration of Route Strategies.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-11-24T14:36:58.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428488/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428488/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428488/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-11-16","M61","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the effects on traffic flow and congestion of the omission of the planned Junction 7 from the M61; and what representations his Department has received on how to mitigate those effects.","false","Biography information for Chris Green","Bolton West","Chris Green","16383"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428489","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-11-19","<p>The UK’s recovery rate for construction and demolition waste reached 86% in 2012, exceeding the 70% target for 2020 set out in the Waste Framework Directive. We will continue to monitor progress and take action as required to ensure the UK meets that target.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-11-19T17:33:24.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428489/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428489/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428489/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-11-16","Waste Management","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what progress she has made on meeting the recovery target for construction and demolition waste in the Waste Framework Directive, 2008/98/EC; and what further steps she is taking to meet that target.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","16365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428490","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-11-19","<p>Figures for the last calendar year are provided below. The estimate for EU countries is based on figures obtained from HM Revenue and Customs which draw on information provided by VAT-registered firms. Actual trade levels may be higher.</p><br /><p><strong>Exports to European Member States</strong></p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Breeding cattle</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sheep</p></td><td><p>161</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Poultry</p></td><td><p>10, 354</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Horses, asses and mules</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Other animals</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>10,525</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /><p><strong>Exports to countries outside the EU</strong></p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Poultry</p></td><td><p>4,252</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Horses, asses and mules</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Other animals</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>4,255</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-11-19T17:41:51.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428490/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428490/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428490/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-11-16","Animals: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate she has made of the number of animals exported to (a) EU member states and (b) countries outside the EU in the last year.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","16514"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428491","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-11-19","<p>Dog attacks are not recorded centrally. However, the attached table provides numbers of successful prosecutions against people who have allowed a dog to be dangerously out of control for each of the last two years for which figures are available.</p><p><br></p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="3"><p><strong>Defendants found guilty of offences under section 3 of Dangerous Dogs Act 1991(1)(2)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Section 3 Dangerous Dogs Act 1991</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>715</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>880</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p><br> (1) The figures given in the table relate to persons for whom these offences were the principal offences for which they were dealt with. When a defendant has been found guilty of two or more offences it is the offence for which the heaviest penalty is imposed. Where the same disposal is imposed for two or more offences, the offence selected is the offence for which the statutory maximum penalty is the most severe. (2) Every effort is made to ensure that the figures presented are accurate and complete. However, it is important to note that these data have been extracted from large administrative data systems generated by the courts and police forces. As a consequence, care should be taken to ensure data collection processes and their inevitable limitations are taken into account when those data are used.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><br /><p>Source: Justice Statistics Analytical Services - Ministry of Justice.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-11-19T17:36:20.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428491/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428491/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428491/answer",,