"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428181","Home Office","false","2015-11-24","<p>The Intelligence and Security Committee of Parliament has been briefed on the use of directions under section 94 of the Telecommunications Act 1984.</p><p>In accordance with section 94 subsection (6) of the Telecommunications Act 1984, money may be provided for the purpose of compensating for any losses that are sustained by reason of compliance with directions.</p><p>On 13 January 2015, the Prime Minister asked the Interception of Communications Commissioner to oversee directions issued under section 94 of the Telecommunications Act. The Commissioner will report on his findings, including on the statistics and wider information that can be published about the use of the power without damage to national security, in his next report.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","16310 ; 16312","2015-11-24T17:04:07.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428181/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428181/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428181/answer","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428181/answer/previousversion/30600","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-13","Electronic Surveillance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the Government has paid out any financial compensation on national security directions made under sections 94 of the Telecommunications Act 1984 in the last 30 years.","false","Biography information for Mr David Davis","Haltemprice and Howden","Mr David Davis","16313"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428182","Home Office","false","2015-11-23","<p>Annex B to the Powers for a Purpose Command Paper provided an illustrative list of the main areas in which reservations would be needed in a reserved powers model. The list described the Government’s emerging thinking as the new reserved powers model was being developed. The Government published its full proposals in the draft Wales Bill on 20 October.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-11-23T17:11:51.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428182/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428182/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428182/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-13","Home Office: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, by what process her Department identified the areas of policy within its responsibility proposed for reservation in Annex B of the publication Powers for a Purpose: Towards a lasting devolution settlement for Wales, published on 27 February 2015.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","16150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428183","Home Office","false","2015-11-23","<p>The reservations listed in Schedule 1 to the draft Wales Bill reflect the Government’s view of where the Welsh devolution boundary lies following the devolution of further powers to the Assembly provided for in the draft Bill.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-11-23T17:14:27.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428183/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428183/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428183/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-13","Home Office: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, for what reasons the matters within her Department's responsibility in Schedule 1 of the draft Wales Bill have been designated as reserved.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","16145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428184","Home Office","false","2015-11-23","<p>The Wales Office is the lead Government department on the draft Wales Bill, and is the primary point of contact with the Welsh Government on matters related to the draft Bill.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-11-23T17:13:11.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428184/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428184/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428184/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-13","Home Office: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many times she has (a) met and (b) corresponded with a minister of the Welsh Government on the draft Wales Bill in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","16146"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428185","Home Office","false","2015-11-19","<p>Acquiring this information would involve examining each individual case record held by UKVI for the category. To do so would incur a disproportionate cost.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-11-19T17:45:56.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428185/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428185/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428185/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-13","Overseas Students: English Language","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many Tier 4 visas have been issued to students entering the UK to study English as a foreign language as their principal area of study in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","16213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428186","Home Office","false","2015-11-18","<p>Decisions on future funding of the National Wildlife Crime Unit will be made as part of the current Spending Review process.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-11-18T18:07:13.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428186/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428186/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428186/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-13","National Wildlife Crime Unit: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans the Government has to renew funding of the National Wildlife Crime Unit after March 2016.","false","Biography information for Gerald Jones","Merthyr Tydfil and Rhymney","Gerald Jones","16200"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428187","Home Office","false","2015-11-18","<p>The Home Office does not record the cost to the public purse of provision of (a) accommodation and (b) support services for asylum seekers within individual counties.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-11-18T17:45:52.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428187/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428187/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428187/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-13","Asylum: Gloucestershire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the cost to the public purse of provision of (a) accommodation and (b) support services for asylum seekers was in Gloucestershire in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Richard Graham","Gloucester","Richard Graham","16171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428188","Home Office","false","2015-11-18","<p>The Home Office has made no specific assessment of the number of crimes committed by people with gambling problems.</p><p>The most recent crime statistics published by the Office for National Statistics showed that overall crime fell by 8% in the year to June 2015, according to the Crime Survey for England and Wales. Crime has now fallen by more than a quarter since June 2010, with just over 2.9 million fewer crimes a year.</p><p>It is for Chief Constables and Police and Crime Commissioners to decide crime priorities at a local level, and the most appropriate response in their areas.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-11-18T18:05:49.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428188/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428188/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428188/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-13","Crime: Gambling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the number of crimes committed by people with gambling problems.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","16206"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428189","Home Office","false","2015-11-18","<p>Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs) are submitted to the National Crime Agency under two pieces of legislation: the Proceeds of Crime Act 2002 for suspicions of money laundering, or the Terrorism Act 2000 for suspicions of terrorist financing.</p><p>The National Crime Agency publishes annual SARs statistics. The reporting period for these publications is from October to September. The figures requested fall across this reporting period. Data for April 2014 to September 2014 can be obtained from the 2013-2014 SARs Annual Report, which is available on the NCA website: http://www.nationalcrimeagency.gov.uk/publications/464-2014-sars-annual-report. Data for October 2014 to March 2015 will be available in the 2014-2015 SARs Annual Report, which is due to be published shortly.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-11-18T17:48:24.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428189/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428189/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428189/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-13","National Crime Agency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many suspicious activity reports relating to (a) the Proceeds of Crime Act 2002 and (b) the Terrorism Act 2000 have been submitted to the National Crime Agency in the last financial year.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","16286"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428190","Home Office","false","2015-11-19","<p>The National Crime Agency was established on 7 October 2013 and, at that time there were eight human trafficking investigations under way.</p><p>Between 7 October 2013 and 6 October 2014 the NCA commenced a further eight NCA human trafficking investigations.</p><p>Between 7 October 2014 and 7 Oct 2015 the NCA commenced a further 11 human trafficking investigation. In addition, over the same period, the NCA has provided specialist support to over 60 investigations led by other law enforcement agencies involving human trafficking.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-11-19T17:28:23.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428190/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428190/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428190/answer","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428190/answer/previousversion/30601","Biography information for Karen Bradley","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-13","Human Trafficking: Criminal Investigation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many investigations have been commenced by the National Crime Agency into human trafficking, in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","16287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428191","Home Office","false","2015-11-20","<p>The National Crime Agency (NCA) disseminates intelligence and information relating to child sexual exploitation for police forces to investigate on a regular basis.</p><p>The NCA made the following number of disseminations in relation to child sexual exploitation and abuse, which includes on-line abuse, to territorial police forces in the UK:</p><p>2014 - 3664</p><p>2015 (to 30 September) - 4071</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-11-20T14:53:24.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428191/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428191/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428191/answer","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428191/answer/previousversion/30602","Biography information for Karen Bradley","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-13","Offences against Children: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many cases of online child abuse were referred from the National Crime Agency to individual police forces in (a) 2014 and (b) 2015.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","16288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428192","Home Office","false","2015-11-20","<p>Reallocations from central Government funding to the police are set out in a Written Ministerial Statement published alongside the Police Grant Report each year. Decisions on funding for 2016/17 will be taken after the Spending Review reports later this month and reallocations will be published in the usual way.</p><p>For 2015/16, reallocations totalled £177 million (rounded to the nearest £1million) and are listed below for your reference.</p><p>In addition, a further £564 m illion was allocated in respect of counter-terrorism policing.</p><p>Police Innovation Fund 70</p><p>Police Knowledge Fund 5</p><p>Independent Police Complaints Commission (for the transfer of integrity functions) 30</p><p>College of Policing (for direct entry schemes) 5</p><p>City of London National and International Capital City Grant 3</p><p>HMIC (for PEEL inspection regime) 9</p><p>Police Special Grant 15</p><p>Major Programmes 40</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-11-20T15:20:37.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428192/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428192/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428192/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-13","Police: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much she expects to be top-sliced from the (a) 2015-16 and (b) 2016-17 police grant; and from what areas that funding will be top-sliced.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","16232"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428193","Home Office","false","2015-11-20","<p>Tackling child sexual exploitation is a top priority for this Government. Significant progress has been made since the launch of the “Tackling CSE” report in March 2015. We have prioritised child sexual abuse as a national threat in the Strategic Policing Requirement, setting a clear expectation on police forces to collaborate across force boundaries, to safeguard children, to share intelligence and to share best practice. All forces are training all police staff to respond to child sexual abuse, including call handlers, PCSOs, police officers, detectives and specialist investigators. And in January we will be launching a new national whistleblowing helpline for any employee - regardless of sector -to report bad practice in relation to child abuse. We have delivered the vast majority of a £7 million funding programme to support non-statutory organisations that have experienced a surge in demand on their services. This funding is to support the victims and survivors of sexual abuse, including children of all ages.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2015-11-20T15:22:33.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428193/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428193/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428193/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-13","Offences against Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what procedures her Department has established to safeguard 16 and 17 year olds who are victims of sexual exploitation.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","16240"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428194","Home Office","false","2015-11-17","<p>The government relies on the evidence of the independent Advisory Council on the Misuse of Drugs, whose most recent report on cannabis, Cannabis Classification and Public Health, concluded that cannabis is a “significant public health issue and can unquestionably cause harm to individuals and society”. The full report can be accessed here:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/acmd-cannabis-classification-and-public-health-2008.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-11-17T17:43:32.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428194/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428194/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428194/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-13","Cannabis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will publish the evidential basis which shows that cannabis is harmful, cited in the Government response to the epetition, We demand the British Government reschedule cannabis.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","16250"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428196","Home Office","false","2015-11-25","<p>There is not a formal service standard for deciding further submissions from failed asylum seekers. The Home Office is balancing resource between those failed asylum seekers with no leave to remain who have made further submissions on the one hand and, on the other, those who were granted a limited period of leave following the refusal of their application who have outstanding applications for Further Leave.</p><p>With regard to further submissions lodged by failed asylum seekers, there is dedicated resource in place to decide cases in the existing stock of further submissions and to also decide new submissions quickly, wherever possible within 5 days of their being lodged. With regard to cases in the stock of further submissions, the Home Office is prioritising cases where applicants are in receipt of asylum support and cases where the applicant may be removed from the United Kingdom in the eventuality their submission is refused. The Home Office will also give priority to further submissions case that have been outstanding for the longest period of time.</p><p>The figures in the below table relate to failed asylum seekers who had outstanding further submissions as of 30 June 2015:</p><p>Timescale (Years) Total</p><p>1 - 2 2383</p><p>2 - 3 1426</p><p>3 or more 1267</p><p>Total 5076</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","16090","2015-11-25T15:55:32.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428196/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428196/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/428196/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-11-13","Asylum: Applications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many decisions on further submissions related to asylum claims that are outstanding have been waiting for longer than (a) one year, (b) two years and (c) three years for a decision.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Smith","Oxford East","Mr Andrew Smith","16091"
